===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term/t|enm|sake||sake, cause}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|sacu||cause, lawsuit, legal action, complaint, issue, dispute}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*sakō||affair, thing, charge, accusation, matter}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*sag-||to investigate}}. Akin to {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|saak|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|sake|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term/t|nl|zaak}} "cause, thing", {{etyl|de|-}} {{term/t|de|Sache}} "thing, legal cause", {{etyl|da|-}} {{term/t|da|sag}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term/t|sv|sak}}, {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|𐍃𐌰𐌺𐌾𐍉|sc=Goth|tr=sakjo|lang=got||dispute, argument}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|sōcn||inquiry, prosecution}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|sēcan||to seek}}. More at [[soke]], [[soken]], [[seek]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{enPR|sāk}}, {{IPA|/seɪk/}}
* {{audio|en-us-sake.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪk}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# [[cause|Cause]], [[interest]] or [[account]].
#* For the sake of argument
# [[purpose|Purpose]] or [[end]]; [[reason]].
#* For old times' sake
# The benefit or regard of someone or something.
#* {{quote-book|year=1897|author=[[w:Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill]]
|title=[[w:The Celebrity|The Celebrity]]
|chapter=1|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2341853W
|passage=When I gave a dinner there was generally a cover laid for him. I liked the man for his own '''sake''', and even had he promised to turn out a celebrity it would have had no weight with me.}}
#* '''2005''', {{w|Plato}}, ''Sophist''. Translation by Lesley Brown. [[w:Stephanus pagination|242a-b]].
#*: But it will be for your '''sake''' that we'll undertake to refute this thesis,{{...}}
# {{qualifier|obsolete except in phrases}} [[contention|Contention]], [[strife]]; [[guilt]], [[sin]], [[accusation]] or charge.
#* And unto Adam He said, Because thou hast hearkened unto the voice of thy wife, and hast eaten of the tree, of which I commanded thee, saying, Thou shalt not eat of it: cursed is the ground for thy '''sake'''; in sorrow shalt thou eat of it all the days of thy life. &mdash; ''Genesis 3:17''

=====Usage notes=====

* The word ''sake'' is generally used in constructions of the form "for X's sake" or "for the sake of X", where X is a noun. (See the quotations above, [[for sake of]], and [[for the sake of]].) 

* Garner's ''Modern American Usage'' notes it is common to write an apostrophe rather than apostrophe–ess in this construction when the noun ends in an /s/ or /z/ sound:  ''[[for appearance' sake]], [[for goodness' sake]]''.

